"CRF_to_FI.py" shows source code for the experiment phase which AOs responded under CRF for 1000 ticks and then transitioned to FI schedules.
"CRF_to_FR.py" shows source code for the experiment phase which AOs responded under CRF for 1000 ticks and then transitioned to FR schedules.
"CriticalValue&ResponseRate.xlsx" contains 5% upper-tail critical values of response rates under the CRF-to-EXT schedules, calculated from empirical null distributions.
The empirical null distribution for each mutation rate was generated by "NullDistribution.py".
"IC_CrfToFI.R" shows R script used to calculate and visualize indices of curvature.
"data" contains the raw data and cumulative records from the experiments.

index of curvature: Fry, W., Kelleher, R. T., & Cook, L. (1960). A mathematical index of performance on fixed-interval schedules of reinforcement. Journal of the Experimental Analysis of Behavior, 3(3), 193–199. https://doi.org/10.1901/jeab.1960.3-193

To calculate the index of curvature (IC), Fry et al. (1960) divided each interval into n equal segments and approximated the integral using these segments. 
This procedure is necessary because time is a continuous variable and the area under the cumulative record cannot be calculated exactly from continuous data.
In the present study, however, behavior was recorded in ticks, which are discrete.
Therefore, instead of dividing an interval into n segments, we calculated the area directly from the cumulative counts between adjacent ticks. 
This approach avoids the need for numerical approximation and yields an exact area for the discrete data.
